<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/31''>31</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">May won&acirc;&#128;&#153;t give up the fight for better&nbsp;trains</h1>


<p class="published"> 5 December 2006</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>As the First Great Western (<span class="caps">FGW</span>) December 2006 timetable comes into force on December 10, Theresa May continues to press for a decent service to Maidenhead and Twyford.</p>

	<p>Theresa explained: <em>&acirc;&#128;&#152;The December 2006 timetable is simply not good enough for the large numbers of commuters that travel from Maidenhead and Twyford and on the branch lines every day. The 2,500 signature petition led to small improvements but nowhere near what was needed.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;I have met with <span class="caps">FGW</span> and Network Rail again recently to discuss these issues and although they accepted that the timetable was not ideal none of them were willing to take the blame for the unacceptable provisions to Maidenhead and Twyford set out in the new timetable. I have also raised the issue in a meeting with the Transport minister.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;But as if coping with the December 2006 timetable wasn&acirc;&#128;&#153;t bad enough. Now we are being told that we need to comment now on the timetable for December 2007. <span class="caps">FGW</span> tell me that, due to the large number of complaints they received for the December 2006 timetable, they will not be holding a long consultation period for December 2007.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;This is simply unacceptable. They seem to think that if they don&acirc;&#128;&#153;t let people comment on the timetable they can claim there is no opposition to the proposals.&Acirc;&nbsp;</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;I have been informed that any comments submitted after 18 January 2007 will be unlikely to be considered. So please let <span class="caps">FGW</span> know your views <span class="caps">NOW</span>! And please do copy me into all your correspondence with them on this issue.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;I shall be pushing for a full reinstatement of all semi-fast and fast services which were lost in the December 2006 timetable. I shall also be pressing for further improvements to the Maidenhead and Twyford services following the investments by <span class="caps">FGW</span> and Network Rail over the next few years and for better branch line connections.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;<span class="caps">FGW</span> will be spending &Acirc;&pound;150million by the end of 2007 on refurbishment and replacement of their rolling stock and Network Rail are spending &Acirc;&pound;750million over 2-3 years on their tracks and infrastructure. Maidenhead and Twyford must be able to see the benefit of this expenditure.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;If you would like to comment to <span class="caps">FGW</span> in person, Richard Rowland, General Manager for the Thames Valley area, will be at Maidenhead station on the evening of Monday 11th January between 4-7pm, Twyford on Tuesday 12th between 4-7pm and London Paddington on the 14th between 4-7pm.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;Alternatively on Monday 11th December I shall be at Maidenhead and Twyford stations during the early morning peak &acirc;&#128;&#147; I shall be happy to speak with any of you about the new service and discuss improvements we can insist on for the future.&acirc;&#128;&#153;</em></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Trains, Services</p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/32''>32</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">May raises trains and third Thames Bridge in meeting with transport&nbsp;minister</h1>


<p class="published"> 5 December 2006</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Today Theresa May joined a delegation of Thames Valley MPs and local businesses to press the Transport Minister for better transport infrastructure in the Thames Valley area.</p>

	<p>Theresa explained: <em>&acirc;&#128;&#152;Today at a meeting with Transport Minster Gillian Merron I pressed the Government to improve our train service and for the need for a third Thames Bridge to relieve Sonning Bridge.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;The meeting was a joint meeting of a cross-party group of Thames Valley MPs and businesses who are members of the Thames Valley Economic Partnership with the Minister to press for Government action to improve transport links in our area. <span class="caps">TVEP</span> members include key multi-nationals like 3, Microsoft, Prudential, Vodaphone, Dell, Cisco, Oracle and Siemens.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;The message was clear. Without better transport infrastructure business will no longer want to locate in the Thames Valley. That means we would lose jobs and economic activity in Maidenhead and the local area, but it would also mean a loss for the UK.&Acirc;&nbsp; Multi-national businesses locate in our area because of good transport links and many believe we are reaching a tipping point where failure to act by the Government will mean businesses will move out. &Acirc;&nbsp;For example, <span class="caps">TVEP</span> has calculated that business spends over &Acirc;&pound;8million a year in the cost of taxis to Heathrow because there are no direct rail links from our area to Heathrow. If just six corporates left the Thames Valley it could mean the loss of 23,500 jobs and over &Acirc;&pound;1 billion of economic activity.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;I raised the impact of the slow deterioration in our train service, the need to improve the Great Western mainline and capacity at Reading station and the need to get trains to Maidenhead back on the mainline.&Acirc;&nbsp; I also told the Minister that if Crossrail stops at Maidenhead it will mean a worse service for local people.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;I also emphasised the need for a third bridge over the Thames to relieve Sonning Bridge and improve access north to south in the Thames Valley.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;I want to see Government action on these issues. and I shall continue to press them for better transport infrastructure for Maidenhead and the wider Thames Valley.&acirc;&#128;&#153;</em></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Trains, Services</p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/34''>34</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">May witnesses new train timetable chaos at first&nbsp;hand</h1>


<p class="published">12 December 2006</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>On Monday morning Theresa May joined commuters in Maidenhead and Twyford to experience first hand FGW&acirc;&#128;&#153;s new December 2006 timetable.</p>

	<p>Theresa explained: <em>&acirc;&#128;&#152;The first days of the new timetable were an unmitigated disaster. Peak hour trains were late, overcrowded and some were even cancelled. &Acirc;&nbsp;Passengers were left standing on platforms as others tried desperately to squeeze onto the few fast trains left in the timetable.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;I have told <span class="caps">FGW</span> for months that their continual cuts to services for Maidenhead and Twyford would only lead to further problems. Now my fears have been confirmed and the service only gets worse and worse.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;On Monday morning I saw trains arriving at Twyford and Maidenhead in the morning peak which were already almost full to capacity. It was bad enough at Twyford &acirc;&#128;&#147; a few people were able to squeeze in &ndash; but impossible at Maidenhead.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;It is appalling for <span class="caps">FGW</span> to allow passengers to be packed in like sardines on services which then run slow, despite being labelled a &ldquo;fast service.&rdquo;</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;FGW&acirc;&#128;&#153;s level of service is simply unacceptable. Now they&acirc;&#128;&#153;ve given us just five weeks to tell them what we think before they put together the timetable for December 2007. I will continue my campaign to improve services and I urge anyone with a complaint about the trains to contact <span class="caps">FGW</span> at <a href="mailto:fgwfeedback@firstgroup.com">fgwfeedback@firstgroup.com</a>, copying me in at <a href="mailto:mayt@parliament.uk">mayt@parliament.uk</a> .</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;Fewer services, more crowding, delayed services and angry commuters &acirc;&#128;&#147; FGW&acirc;&#128;&#153;s new timetable has not got off to a good start.&acirc;&#128;&#153;</em></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Trains, Services</p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/35''>35</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">May calls on FGW to lose&nbsp;franchise</h1>


<p class="published">15 January 2007</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Local MP Theresa May has called for <span class="caps">FGW</span> to lose its franchise to provide train services to Maidenhead, Twyford and the branch lines. Theresa has also secured a debate in Parliament on Thursday 18 January on the problems with local train services.</p>

	<p>Theresa said, <em>&acirc;&#128;&#156;The December 2006 timetable has been a disaster. I continue to get emails every day from passengers complaining about overcrowding, delays and cancellations. The recent changes to the timetable have done little to help. We will only get a decent service back when we have a train operator committed to commuter services and a Government that is interested in passengers&acirc;&#128;&#153; needs not its own targets.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;I will be raising these issues in Parliament on 18 January in a short debate which I have called on train services for Maidenhead and Twyford.&Acirc;&nbsp; I didn&acirc;&#128;&#153;t get satisfactory answers from <span class="caps">FGW</span> now let&acirc;&#128;&#153;s see what the Minister has to say. &Acirc;&nbsp;Government must take their share of the blame as the specification they set for the timetable was inadequate.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;But whatever they say I&acirc;&#128;&#153;m now at the point where I believe we need a different company serving Maidenhead and Twyford and the branch lines, and that <span class="caps">FGW</span> should lose this part of the franchise.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;I have joined with other Thames Valley MPs to call for a meeting with the Secretary of State, <span class="caps">FGW</span> and Network Rail &acirc;&#128;&#147; with all three present they will no longer be able to simply point the finger of blame and avoid taking any action. &Acirc;&nbsp;And we are also asking the <span class="caps">HSE</span> to look again into the problem of overcrowding on trains. It is remarkable that there are laws protecting chickens from overcrowding but nothing to protect human commuters!</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;My constituents have suffered poor train services for too long under <span class="caps">FGW</span>. Its time for the Government to act.&acirc;&#128;&#157;</em></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Trains, Services</p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/36''>36</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">May slams FGW&acirc;&#128;&#153;s failure to listen to local&nbsp;passengers</h1>


<p class="published">10 January 2007</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Theresa May MP has attacked <span class="caps">FGW</span> for its failure to listen to local passengers&acirc;&#128;&#153; complaints following revelations that <span class="caps">FGW</span> have improved services from Oxford and ignored the needs of passengers from Maidenhead and Twyford.</p>

	<p>Theresa explained, <em>&acirc;&#128;&#152;I was appalled when I saw the latest timetable changes from <span class="caps">FGW</span> which are due to come in next Monday 15 January.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;They claim they have listened to passengers&acirc;&#128;&#153; complaints but in fact they&acirc;&#128;&#153;ve completely ignored people travelling from Maidenhead and Twyford. &Acirc;&nbsp;For us the service will get worse. The 0726 which currently starts, empty, at Twyford will now start at Oxford. There are few enough seats at Maidenhead on this already.&Acirc;&nbsp; What on earth will it be like when it starts from Oxford?</em></p>

	<p>_&rsquo;What is galling is that this was the train added to the timetable following our campaign last year. Only two days ago they were boasting that this was a &acirc;&#128;&#156;significant investment in Twyford and Maidenhead&acirc;&#128;&#157;. Now they&acirc;&#128;&#153;re undoing all that.</p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;I am deeply disappointed that <span class="caps">FGW</span> have chosen to ignore the concerns of Maidenhead and Twyford commuters. &Acirc;&nbsp;I&acirc;&#128;&#153;ve had nearly 600 emails complaining about the new timetable since it started.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;<span class="caps">FGW</span> clearly have no interest in providing a decent service to their customers.&Acirc;&nbsp; I am meeting with Alison Forster, the Managing Director of <span class="caps">FGW</span>, &Acirc;&nbsp;tomorrow and I have insisted that she bring to our meeting proposals for real improvements to the service for Maidenhead and Twyford as these current changes are simply unacceptable.&acirc;&#128;&#153;</em></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Trains, Services</p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/37''>37</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">May: new paint won&acirc;&#128;&#153;t make them go&nbsp;faster</h1>


<p class="published"> 7 January 2007</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Local MP Theresa May has attacked <span class="caps">FGW</span> for offering new livery on the trains rather than a better service.</p>

	<p>Theresa explained, <em>&lsquo;I&acirc;&#128;&#153;m astounded. Just when commuters are being forced to endure fewer trains, cancellations, late running and awful overcrowding, <span class="caps">FGW</span> are spending money and time on cosmetic enhancements to their fleet.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;What we want is a decent service, not pretty trains. New paint won&acirc;&#128;&#153;t make the trains go faster.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;I am afraid that this is just another example of <span class="caps">FGW</span> missing the point. I will leave <span class="caps">FGW</span> in no doubt that it&acirc;&#128;&#153;s the timetable that needs a make-over not the trains.&rsquo;</em><br>
&Acirc;&nbsp;<br>
Theresa will be attending a meeting with Alison Forster, Managing Director of <span class="caps">FGW</span>, and other Thames Valley MPs later this week. However, Theresa was adamant that she should have a private meeting with Ms Forster specifically to discuss the needs of Maidenhead and Twyford and the branch lines.</p>

	<p>As Theresa said, <em>&acirc;&#128;&#152;It is clear that the December 2006 timetable severely sidelines the needs of the Thames Valley in favour of longer distance journeys, and therefore I am glad to meet with Alison Forster and other Thames Valley MPs to discuss possible improvements.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;But there are specific problems for my constituents travelling from Maidenhead and Twyford and the branch line stations of Wargrave, Cookham and Furze Platt. I think it is vital that I meet with Alison Forster on my own to press home the need for significant improvements. That way I can make sure she knows about all the complaints raised by passengers in the over 500 emails I have received. This train timetable is affecting people&acirc;&#128;&#153;s lives and <span class="caps">FGW</span> must act now to improve it.&rsquo;</em></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Trains, Services</p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/38''>38</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">May: FGW the ball is in your&nbsp;court</h1>


<p class="published">19 January 2007</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Theresa May MP held a debate on the state of the train service for Maidenhead and Twyford in the House of Commons on 18 January. During the debate the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Transport, Tom Harris MP, admitted that <span class="caps">FGW</span> must listen to their passengers and add more services to the Government&acirc;&#128;&#153;s minimum level specification.</p>

	<p>Theresa explains, <em>&acirc;&#128;&#152;The debate meant I could tell the Minister face to face how bad our trains are and explain the problems for local people.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;The Minister was quite clear that <span class="caps">FGW</span> are delivering performance &acirc;&#128;&#156;below the national level&acirc;&#128;&#157;.&Acirc;&nbsp; He also made it clear that the service specification set by the Government is a minimum and that <span class="caps">FGW</span> should add value to these specifications after listening to the needs of their customers.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;That flies in the face of claims by <span class="caps">FGW</span> that they are simply having to deliver the service specification given by Government.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;The Minister&acirc;&#128;&#153;s statement that he looks &acirc;&#128;&#156;to First Great Western, to listen to its passengers and stakeholders and to make changes to meet their needs&acirc;&#128;&#157; gives a pretty clear message to <span class="caps">FGW</span> &acirc;&#128;&#147; do something about the problem!</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;The ball is now in FGW&acirc;&#128;&#153;s court.&Acirc;&nbsp; Despite saying there were no carriages available to improve services they&acirc;&#128;&#153;ve miraculously found some for the Bristol area so they&acirc;&#128;&#153;d better find some more for Maidenhead and Twyford services and give us the trains people need.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;We don&acirc;&#128;&#153;t want excuses and we don&acirc;&#128;&#153;t want changes that make life better somewhere else down the line but don&acirc;&#128;&#153;t help Maidenhead and Twyford.&Acirc;&nbsp; We want action to make life better for local passengers.&acirc;&#128;&#157;</em></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Trains, Westminster News</p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/40''>40</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">May: now it&acirc;&#128;&#153;s time for&nbsp;action</h1>


<p class="published">31 January 2007</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>After two debates in the House of Commons on <span class="caps">FGW</span> and their poor service to their customers, Theresa May MP is calling for them to step up to the plate and finally take some action.</p>

	<p>Theresa explains, <em>&acirc;&#128;&#152;In my debate on FGW&Acirc;&nbsp;the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Transport, Tom Harris, made it clear that the Government agrees that <span class="caps">FGW</span> have provided an &acirc;&#128;&#152;unacceptable level of service&acirc;&#128;&#153; to their customers.  He also clarified that, despite claims to the contrary, the Government expect <span class="caps">FGW</span> to add to their base service level commitment in order to provide an adequate service. He made it clear that the Government expect <span class="caps">FGW</span> to listen to their customers and respond to their needs. The Government expect <span class="caps">FGW</span> to accept culpability for what Tom Harris term their &acirc;&#128;&#152;disastrous performance&acirc;&#128;&#153;.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;I know they have been continuously notified of customer dissatisfaction since the new timetable was introduced. I have received almost 1000 emails complaining about <span class="caps">FGW</span>&rsquo;s appalling services.&Acirc;&nbsp; People complain about unreliable, overcrowded services on a timetable which clearly lacks enough fast and semi fast services to deal with the number of commuters from Maidenhead and Twyford.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;I have put these points to Alison Forster, <span class="caps">FGW</span>&rsquo;s&Acirc;&nbsp;Managing Director, but am writing again to set out the many complaints I have received and urge them to do something to improve the daily commute for my constituents.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;We have&Acirc;&nbsp;told <span class="caps">FGW</span> their failings. Now it is time for them to act. If they fail to do so, after the Government&acirc;&#128;&#153;s very clear requests, I shall be going back to the Department for Transport to raise the issue of whether <span class="caps">FGW</span> should be allowed to continue providing commuter services to London.&acirc;&#128;&#153;</em></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Trains, Westminster News</p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/41''>41</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Government u-turn on&nbsp;trains!</h1>


<p class="published">12 February 2007</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>The Department of Transport have finally agreed to meet with local MP Theresa May and others to discuss FGW&acirc;&#128;&#153;s appalling service.</p>

	<p>Theresa explained, <em>&acirc;&#128;&#152;Early in January I and several other Thames Valley MPs wrote to Douglas Alexander, Secretary of State for Transport requesting a meeting regarding <span class="caps">FGW</span>.&Acirc;&nbsp; On Thursday last week I received a letter from Tom Harris, Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Transport, flatly refusing this meeting.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;He distanced himself and the Department from FGW&acirc;&#128;&#153;s failures and assured me that, as they were &acirc;&#128;&#152;monitoring&acirc;&#128;&#153; FGW&acirc;&#128;&#153;s performance, there was no need for a meeting.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;I was obviously quite annoyed and was about to take this up with the Department for Transport when Douglas Alexander himself emailed me to apologise for Mr Harris&acirc;&#128;&#153; response and to confirm that a meeting would be possible in the next few weeks.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;I am delighted that the Department have finally agreed to this meeting. And I will press to ensure that both Network Rail and <span class="caps">FGW</span> are represented in order to avoid any &acirc;&#128;&#152;buck-passing&acirc;&#128;&#153;.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;I welcome this Government u-turn. I hope it means they have realised that commuters from the Thames Valley are simply fed up with <span class="caps">FGW</span> appalling service and will no longer put up with the disinterest showed by the Government, Network Rail and <span class="caps">FGW</span> themselves.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;I will certainly use this meeting to impress upon them that people can no longer tolerate this appalling service from <span class="caps">FGW</span>. Something has to be done, and it is up to the Government, Network Rail and <span class="caps">FGW</span> to work together to make this happen.&acirc;&#128;&#153;</em></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Trains, Westminster News</p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/42''>42</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Theresa may encourages young people to show they're 'here to help'</h1>


<p class="published">20 February 2007</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Today Theresa May&Acirc;&nbsp;encouraged young people in Maidenhead to apply for a Save the children &acirc;&#128;&#152;Here to HELP&acirc;&#128;&#153; award, funded by British Gas. Many awards of up to &Acirc;&pound;1000 and a few of up to &Acirc;&pound;3000 are available for projects which improve something in the local community.</p>

	<p>The awards are to help young people get involved in dynamic and lasting community projects. The awards have been running for nearly two years and have had a positive impact on the lives of over 10,000 children in England, Scotland and Wales.  Theresa explained, <em>&acirc;&#128;&#152;This is a great opportunity to improve our local area. So if you&acirc;&#128;&#153;re a young person who can think of a good project for your local area you should apply for an award.</em></p>

	<p><em>&lsquo;Save the Children will be offering &Acirc;&pound;1000 awards from projects that deal with health, education and the protection of children. And &Acirc;&pound;3000 awards for projects that specifically aim to benefit the most marginalised in society, such as poor children who have less chance of living in adequate housing and getting basic services like healthcare and education.&Acirc;&nbsp; I am sure that many young people in Maidenhead will be able to come up with wonderful proposals for these awards. Do keep me informed of your applications and their successes!&acirc;&#128;&#153;</em></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Westminster News, </p>
</div>
