<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Good news on Sandford&nbsp;farm</h1>


<p class="published">12 December 2007</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Theresa May has welcomed the decision made by Wokingham Borough Council to turn down plans to build a combined residential and business complex on the Sandford Farm landfill site.</p>

	<p>The proposal, which had included plans for 150 new retirement homes, followed a number of proposals for the site that were rejected by Wokingham Borough Council. Local residents in Woodley had expressed concern about the loss of amenity and poor provisions for parking at the development. Residents in Charvil were worried about increased traffic through local roads.&Acirc;&nbsp;The construction of the development would also have dramatically increased the traffic levels in the local area, causing further disruption to residents.</p>

	<p>Theresa said, <em>&ldquo;I am pleased that Wokingham Council has listened to what local people want and has rejected this latest plan for Sandford Farm. The area is a valuable green space enjoyed by local residents and wildlife and I will continue to campaign on their behalf for it to stay that way.&rdquo;</em></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Housing and development, </p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/57''>57</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Guarantee on&nbsp;Crossrail</h1>


<p class="published">18 December 2007</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Theresa May has obtained significant guarantees from the Government about the impact of Crossrail on Maidenhead and Twyford. Speaking in the House of Commons, Theresa argued that the Crossrail line should be extended to Reading saying that <em>&acirc;&#128;&#156;if the Crossrail line does not extend from Maidenhead to Reading they (constituents in Twyford) would really lose out&acirc;&#128;&#157;</em>. She asked Transport Minister Tom Harris to guarantee that the line could be extended to Reading under existing legislation, meaning that the extension could be done more quickly. In response, the Minister stated that <em>&acirc;&#128;&#156;the Government are committed to making a decision on the safeguarding of the route from Maidenhead to Reading for future possible extension of Crossrail to Reading&acirc;&#128;&#157;</em>. Importantly, he confirmed that the line could be extended under existing legislation and it would not have to go through the same lengthy parliamentary procedures as this Bill.</p>

	<p>Theresa also raised the problem of the impact of Crossrail on commuters in Maidenhead saying <em>&acirc;&#128;&#156;I am concerned that my constituents in Maidenhead and Twyford could find themselves with a greatly reduced service and amenity when Crossrail is introduced, because they might lose First Great Western services and end up at the end of a metro line, which would be a slow stopping service that would take twice as long to get to Paddington as it does at the moment&acirc;&#128;&#157;</em>.</p>

	<p>The Minister gave a commitment that <em>&acirc;&#128;&#156;whenever the First Great Western franchise is renewed, we will ensure that due attention is paid to the points that she has raised about the level of Crossrail services at Maidenhead&acirc;&#128;&#157;</em>. Commenting on the Government&acirc;&#128;&#153;s guarantee, Theresa said <em>&acirc;&#128;&#156;extending the Crossrail line to Reading would make rail travel for people in both Twyford and Maidenhead so much easier. I am pleased that we now have confirmation that the extension could be done under existing legislation which would make the process much quicker.&Acirc;&nbsp;I am also pleased that the need to give proper thought to services to Maidenhead has been accepted by the Government&acirc;&#128;&#157;</em>.</p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Trains, </p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/58''>58</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Campainging for broadband in Waltham St&nbsp;Lawrence</h1>


<p class="published">24 December 2007</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Theresa May has launched a campaign in Parliament to bring broadband to Waltham St Lawrence.&Acirc;&nbsp;Households in the village are in the 0.2 per cent of households in the country who still can&acirc;&#128;&#153;t receive broadband internet.&Acirc;&nbsp;Residents have long campaigned for the service to be extended to them and others in rural areas without broadband.</p>

	<p>Theresa May has taken on the cause and has launched a campaign to get the Government and Ofcom to work with broadband suppliers to improve access to broadband and telecommunication services in rural areas.&Acirc;&nbsp;She has tabled an Early Day Motion, a formal petition for a parliamentary debate, and is working with organisations such as the Community Broadband Network to raise the profile of this important issue.</p>

	<p>Theresa says, <em>&ldquo;For those who live in remote areas, or indeed those who run small businesses based in the countryside, quick and reliable telecommunications services are an increasingly important means of conducting day-to-day life.&Acirc;&nbsp;Yet, broadband access is still a problem for many rural communities across the country and rural consumers are, therefore, disadvantaged in this respect.&Acirc;&nbsp;I strongly believe that it is vital for rural areas to have an equal level of service to those in urban areas.&rdquo;</em></p>

	<p><em>&ldquo;I sympathise greatly with the frustration experienced by the residents of Waltham St Lawrence at being in the 0.2 per cent of households unable to receive broadband internet.&Acirc;&nbsp;I sincerely hope that we can bring about a speedy resolution to this problem.&rdquo;</em></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Services, </p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/59''>59</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Bevin boys&nbsp;badge</h1>


<p class="published">24 December 2007</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Theresa May is looking for surviving Bevin Boys in the area to come forward to claim a unique veterans badge as a tribute to their sacrifices during and after the Second World War.</p>

	<p>The Bevin Boys scheme was introduced in 1943 by the Minister for Labour and National Service, Ernest Bevin, in response to an increasing shortage of labour in the coal mining industry. The scheme ran between 1943 and 1948 and involved recruiting men aged between 18 and 25 years to work in coal mines rather than in the armed forces. Some 48,000 men were either selected or volunteered under the scheme.</p>

	<p>Theresa says, <em>&acirc;&#128;&#156;It is important that we never forget the sacrifices that were made both at home and abroad during the war. The Government have decided that to mark the valuable contribution of the Bevin Boys by awarding them with a special badge. If you are a Bevin Boy living in Maidenhead, or you know someone who is, please come forward to claim this fitting tribute&acirc;&#128;&#157;</em></p>

	<p>The first badges will be issued in March next year, to coincide with the 60th anniversary to the demobbing of the last Bevin Boy.&Acirc;&nbsp;All Bevin Boys, whether they are ballotees, optants or volunteers are able to apply.&Acirc;&nbsp;Applications will also be accepted from the widows of Bevin Boys who passed away on or after 20 June 2007 provided a copy of the marriage and death certificate are attached to the application form.&Acirc;&nbsp;Applicants must complete an application form, available by calling the Service Personnel and Veterans Agency helpline on 0800 169 2277 or 01253 866043, or by visiting <a href="http://www.veteransagency.co.uk/">www.veteransagency.co.uk</a></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Uncategorized, </p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/60''>60</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Theresa attacks strike&nbsp;action</h1>


<p class="published">11 January 2008</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>On 10 January, <span class="caps">RMT</span> guards and train drivers at First Great Western voted overwhelmingly to strike over disputes on breakdowns in industrial relations and the use of managers to guard and drive trains.</p>

	<p>Theresa May said, <em>&ldquo;I am dismayed that after all the serious problems rail passengers in Maidenhead and Twyford have had with First Great Western, especially over the Christmas break, they could now be affected by a strike action. When will the <span class="caps">RMT</span> learn that strike action is not the answer? The only people it will hurt are the passengers trying to use the trains to go to work and about their daily business. I would urge both the <span class="caps">RMT</span> and First Great Western to work hard together to reach a reasonable solution as soon as possible.&rdquo;</em></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Services, </p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/61''>61</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Tackling nuisance phone&nbsp;calls</h1>


<p class="published">15 January 2008</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>In response to an issue raised by constituents, Theresa May has written to the Secretary of State for Business, Enterprise &amp; Regulatory Reform to express concern about the extent of nuisance unsolicited telephone calls received by Maidenhead residents.</p>

	<p>Theresa said, <em>&acirc;&#128;&#156;This is an issue which has been raised by Maidenhead residents and I think the Government needs to look closely at it. We all know what a nuisance these calls are but it can also cause great distress to be targeted by recorded messages. I am aware of one case where these unwanted calls have targeted an elderly lady living alone who was distressed by the calls. These are completely unacceptable tactics.&acirc;&#128;&#157;</em></p>

	<p><em>&acirc;&#128;&#156;I hope the Government will take very seriously the concerns that have been voiced by local residents.&acirc;&#128;&#157;</em></p>

	<h3>Text of the letter Theresa May sent to John Hutton, Secretary of State for Business, Enterprise &amp; Regulatory Reform:</h3>

	<p>Rt Hon John Hutton MP<br>
Secretary of State<br>
Department for Business, Enterprise &amp; Regulatory Reform<br>
1 Victoria Street<br>
London<br>
SW1H 0ET</p>

	<p>15th January 2008</p>

	<p>Dear Secretary of State,</p>

	<p>Several of my constituents have contacted me recently with concerns about the number of unsolicited nuisance telephone calls that they are receiving. These phone calls &acirc;&#128;&#147; which are often automated &acirc;&#128;&#147; invariably attempt to sell them a product, or convince the person that they have won a competition that they did not enter. In one case the calls targeted an elderly lady living alone, who was distressed by the calls.</p>

	<p>I am sure that you would agree that these tactics are unscrupulous. As you will be aware, the Privacy and Electronic Communications (EC Directive) Regulations 2003 require that marketers who leave recorded phone messages must obtain the prior consent of the subscriber before they can make that call. It is clear that this is not happening in many cases.</p>

	<p>Unfortunately many people are unaware of the Telephone Preference Service, which offers protection against unsolicited calls.</p>

	<p>I am writing to ask what the Government is planning to do to address this issue, which can cause great distress to many people. I would also be grateful if you could inform me of what measures the Government has taken to increase awareness of the means that already exist by which people can take action to prevent unwanted calls.</p>

	<p>Thank you in advance for your response on this matter. Given the inherent public interest in this issue, I am releasing a copy of this letter to the media.</p>

	<p>Yours sincerely,</p>

	<p>Rt Hon Theresa May MP</p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Uncategorized, </p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/62''>62</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Theresa welcomes FGW double compensation&nbsp;offer</h1>


<p class="published">23 January 2008</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Theresa May has welcomed the move by First Great Western (<span class="caps">FGW</span>) boss Andrew Haines to give regular commuters double compensation following the appalling train service that they have endured over the last year.</p>

	<p>Theresa said, <em>&acirc;&#128;&#156;After the appalling service local commuters have had to put up with over the past year, it is about time they got something back from <span class="caps">FGW</span>. I welcome the move by <span class="caps">FGW</span> boss Andrew Haines to give double compensation to <span class="caps">FGW</span> customers and the recognition from <span class="caps">FGW</span> that local people deserve a better service. However as well as compensation, <span class="caps">FGW</span> need to work much harder to improve the service they offer to local commuters in Maidenhead and Twyford so that this situation never happens again&acirc;&#128;&#157;.</em></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Services, </p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/63''>63</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Post Office&nbsp;closures</h1>


<p class="published">29 January 2008</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Theresa May has pledged to fight plans to shut six post offices in the Maidenhead constituency.</p>

	<p>Theresa said, <em>&acirc;&#128;&#156;I am astounded at this announcement by the Post Office. It is a real kick in the teeth to all those people who rely on their local post office. What&acirc;&#128;&#153;s more, Maidenhead is set to suffer more than many surrounding areas with four closures in the town and another two in the rest of the constituency. What have they got against Maidenhead? Over the years I have fought successfully against Post Office closures and will fight hard against these latest plans. A local Post Office can be a lifeline for many elderly people. Doesn&acirc;&#128;&#153;t the Post Office understand that? I urge everyone who feels strongly about their Post Office to tell me and Royal Mail why it needs to stay open. Let&acirc;&#128;&#153;s make sure Maidenhead&acirc;&#128;&#153;s voice is heard&acirc;&#128;&#157;.</em></p>

	<p>There are six post offices under threat in the Maidenhead area. In Maidenhead the Post Offices in Wooton Way, Bridge Road, Cookham Road and Norfolk Park are under threat. The Post Office in Knowl Hill is also under threat, as is the Post Office on the High Street in Wargrave.</p>

	<p>On average, 20 per cent of Post Offices are under threat nationwide. Closing six out of 19 Post Offices in Maidenhead would mean that Maidenhead would be losing 31.6 per cent of its Post Offices, 11.6 per cent above the national average.</p>

	<p>The public consultation will last for six weeks from 29 January to 11 March.&Acirc;&nbsp;All branches will display posters and those that are likely to be affected by the proposals in the Area Plan will also provide leaflets giving information about proposed changes for the branch.</p>

	<p>The Post Office Ltd also has a copy of the Area plan proposal available on its website at <a href="http://www.postoffice.co.uk/network">www.postoffice.co.uk/network</a> change. Members of the public responding to the public consultation must be able to outline constructive reasons as to why their Post Office should stay open. To respond in writing to the consultation, people should write to Gary Herbert, Network Development Manager, C/o National Consultation Team, <span class="caps">FREEPOST</span> <span class="caps">CONSULTATION</span> <span class="caps">TEAM</span>, or email <a href="mailto:consultation@postoffice.co.uk">consultation@postoffice.co.uk</a>.</p>

	<p>When submitting to the consultation, it would be very useful if local people forwarded their submission to Theresa as well, so that she can assess the amount of local feeling about each branch.</p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Services, </p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/64''>64</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Theresa backs campaign against&nbsp;trafficking</h1>


<p class="published">31 January 2008</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Theresa May gave her support to the Blue Blindfold Campaign launch in the House of Commons on Tuesday 29th January.&Acirc;&nbsp;The campaign, initiated by the UK Human Trafficking Centre, aims to create greater awareness amongst the public about human trafficking through a series of distinct posters displayed on buses throughout the UK with the message, &acirc;&#128;&#152;Don&acirc;&#128;&#153;t close your eyes to human trafficking&acirc;&#128;&#153;.</p>

	<p>Theresa, who is Shadow Minister for Women, said: <em>&acirc;&#128;&#156;This is an excellent initiative that I fully support. Using eye-catching advertising to alert people to the fact that human trafficking is a reality in our towns and cities will increase awareness of this despicable activity.&acirc;&#128;&#157;</em></p>

	<p>The posters are to appear on First, Arriva/Go Ahead and Stagecoach buses throughout the country including Manchester, Leeds, Sheffield and Greater London.</p>

	<p>Nick Kinsella, Head of the UK Human Trafficking Centre said, <em>&acirc;&#128;&#156;It&acirc;&#128;&#153;s important for people to realise that this type of crime is not visible. The victims do not have a voice because they are controlled and they are too scared to ask for help. People must open their eyes to the fact that someone in their community or the person down the road could be a trafficked person.&acirc;&#128;&#157;</em></p>

	<p>The <span class="caps">UKHTC</span>, established in 2006, is the country&acirc;&#128;&#153;s leading centre for expertise helping to deliver operational, tactical and legal support to police forces and other law enforcement agencies engaged in tackling human trafficking. The Blue Blindfold campaign is another example of the ways in which the <span class="caps">UKHTC</span> are tackling this crime.</p>

	<p>The <span class="caps">UKHTC</span> has acted in an advisory capacity for police operations across the country, a number of which have resulted in successful prosecutions for offences relating to human trafficking.</p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Uncategorized, </p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/65''>65</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Theresa opposes new plan for Sandford farm&nbsp;development</h1>


<p class="published"> 4 February 2008</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Theresa May has reacted to reports of yet another plan for development on Sandford Farm. The latest plan is expected to include provision for 800 houses and 150 care village homes.</p>

	<p>Theresa said, <em>&acirc;&#128;&#156;Once again the residents of Charvil, Woodley and Hurst are facing an unwanted plan for development on Sandford Farm. This is a monstrous application. The increase in traffic resulting from the previous plan would have been bad enough. Now the developer is planning nearly 1,000 new homes on the site. Local roads simply will not be able to cope, and there will be a significant loss of local amenity. I urge local residents to stand up against this proposal. I will be objecting strongly and I hope the Council take note of local people&acirc;&#128;&#153;s concerns.&acirc;&#128;&#157;</em></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Housing and development, </p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/67''>67</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Calling all local&nbsp;businesswomen</h1>


<p class="published">18 February 2008</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Women in Maidenhead have been encouraged by Theresa May to enter the prestigious BlackBerry&Acirc;&reg; Women &amp; Technology Awards 2008.</p>

	<p>The Awards celebrate the achievements of women using technology, both within and beyond the IT sector, bringing their outstanding contributions into the public eye.&Acirc;&nbsp;The Awards look to honour the individual (or company) that has achieved success in their field through innovation, management and return on investment via technology.</p>

	<p>The Awards are open to organisations of all sizes and to women from all walks of life.</p>

	<p>Commenting on the Awards, Theresa said: <em>&acirc;&#128;&#156;These prestigious Awards offer women of all backgrounds the opportunity to showcase their work on the national stage. It doesn&acirc;&#128;&#153;t matter if you are working within a <span class="caps">SME</span> or in the public sector, as long as you are succeeding using technology &ndash; these awards offer a real opportunity to gain recognition for your achievements. I encourage all local businesswomen to enter these awards &acirc;&#128;&#147; it would be fantastic to see a winner from Maidenhead&acirc;&#128;&#157;</em></p>

	<p>For further details on the awards or to enter visit: <a href="http://www.blackberrywomentechnologyawards.com/">www.blackberrywomentechnologyawards.com</a> or call Ben Thornton on 020 7395 7179.</p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Uncategorized, </p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/68''>68</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Competition hotting up for the &acirc;&#128;&#152;curry cup&acirc;&#128;&#153;&nbsp;challenge</h1>


<p class="published">19 February 2008</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Theresa May is asking for nominations for the best Indian, Bangladeshi and Pakistani restaurant in the Maidenhead area to compete in the Tiffin Cup.</p>

	<p>Theresa says: <em>&ldquo;I am pleased to have been invited to nominate a local favourite South Asian Restaurant in Maidenhead for the Tiffin Cup. The catering industry does much to boost charitable causes and is an important and very worthy part of our local community. So if you know of a deserving restaurant, please get in touch with me. The final winner will be decided by a special cook-in in London and it would be great to see a local restaurant winning the Cup this year!&rdquo;</em></p>

	<p>This is the third year the Tiffin Cup, organised buy the Rt Hon Keith Vaz MP has run. Last year the winner was the Taj Mahal of Haverfordwest, nominated by Stephen Crabb MP.</p>

	<p>Nominations should be sent by 24th March to the Rt Hon Theresa May MP, House of Commons, London, SW1A 0AA.&Acirc;&nbsp;Once nominations are made, 10 entrants will be short-listed and invited to a special cook-in at Bellamy&acirc;&#128;&#153;s restaurant in Parliament where the overall winner for the UK will be found. The winning restaurant will get a year&rsquo;s supply of Cobra Beer and the 2008 Tiffin Cup. This year, the event is being held to support an orphanage in India.</p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Uncategorized, </p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/69''>69</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Theresa responds to government&acirc;&#128;&#153;s action on&nbsp;FGW</h1>


<p class="published">27 February 2008</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Theresa May has today responded to a decision by Transport Secretary, Ruth Kelly, to issue First Great Western a Remedial Plan Notice to address unacceptably the high levels of train cancellations on the <span class="caps">FGW</span> franchise.</p>

	<p><span class="caps">FGW</span> is being issued with the Notice for exceeding the threshold on cancellations in the second half of last year.</p>

	<p>Commenting on the decision, Theresa&Acirc;&nbsp;said: <em>&ldquo;I welcome the decision by the Government to hold <span class="caps">FGW</span> to account for their disastrous service at the end of last year.&Acirc;&nbsp;A huge number of local commuters had their journeys disrupted by FGW&acirc;&#128;&#153;s continuous blunders. <span class="caps">FGW</span> has already acknowledged that its service was unacceptable and doubled its compensation to season ticket holders.&rdquo;</em></p>

	<p><em>&ldquo;This Notice announced today is effectively an ultimatum to <span class="caps">FGW</span>: improve your service or your contract will be terminated. I will continue to keep a close eye on FGW&acirc;&#128;&#153;s performance, and hope that the Notice will lead to much needed improvements for Maidenhead and Twyford commuters.&rdquo;</em></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Services, </p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/71''>71</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Keep Cookham Road Post Office&nbsp;open</h1>


<p class="published">12 March 2008</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Theresa May last week presented a petition to Parliament signed by a staggering 1,384 people to keep the Cookham Road Post Office open. The Cookham Road Post Office is one of six Post Offices in the Maidenhead area under threat from closure.</p>

	<p>Theresa said, <em>&acirc;&#128;&#156;The huge level of local support for Cookham Road Post Office proves how much people want the Post Office to stay open. There has been so much support for each of the six Post Offices and there are good reasons for keeping them all open. I sincerely hope that the Government will take these into account.&acirc;&#128;&#157;</em></p>

	<p><em>&acirc;&#128;&#156;Maidenhead has been especially badly hit by the closure programme. There were originally six Post Offices under threat, but now the Post Office at Waltham St Lawrence is also being closed. This means that in the Maidenhead constituency, 35 per cent of Post Offices are under threat, well above the national average of 20 per cent of the Post Office network. In Slough and Windsor, only two Post Offices have been threatened, why is Maidenhead being hit so hard?&acirc;&#128;&#157;</em></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Services, </p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/72''>72</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Theresa speaks out against Post Office&nbsp;annoucement</h1>


<p class="published"> 8 April 2008</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>This morning, the Post Office Ltd announced that it was going ahead with closing five out of the six Post Offices in the Maidenhead area threatened with closure.</p>

	<p>Of the six Post Offices, only Bridge Road Post Office in Maidenhead has been saved. Theresa May, who had campaigned hard against the closures, said:</p>

	<p><em>&ldquo;Our Post Offices provide an invaluable to the local community they serve. I am delighted that Bridge Road Post Office has been saved but I am deeply disappointed that the Post Office Ltd has chosen to ignore the strength of local feeling and close five of our Post Offices. It seems that the Post Office and the Government had already made the decision to close 2,500 branches nationally, ignoring the needs of local communities and that was it.&rdquo;</em></p>

	<p><em>&ldquo;As it currently stands, only 24 out of 621 of the Post Offices threatened across the country have been saved from closure and I am pleased that because of the strength of our local campaign, we have ensured that Bridge Road is one of the branches that will be saved.&rdquo;</em></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Services, </p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/73''>73</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Appeal for minor injuries unit in&nbsp;Maidenhead</h1>


<p class="published"> 8 April 2008</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>On the day that the consultation for the East Berkshire <span class="caps">PCT</span> healthcare plan ends, Theresa May has appealed again for East Berkshire <span class="caps">PCT</span> to reconsider their plans not to build a minor injuries unit at St Marks Hospital in Maidenhead.</p>

	<p>Having long campaigned for a minor injuries unit in Maidenhead and other improvements to local healthcare, Theresa will visit St Marks on Monday 14th April to hand over a petition campaigning for a minor injuries unit organised by the Maidenhead Advertiser and signed by thousands of local people.</p>

	<p>Theresa said, <em>&ldquo;The healthcare plan for East Berkshire we saw three months ago was a real slap in the face for Maidenhead. Once again, services were to be significantly improved for people living in Slough and Bracknell, at the expense of people in Maidenhead.&rdquo;</em></p>

	<p><em>&ldquo;I urge Berkshire East <span class="caps">PCT</span> to show they are listening to what local people want, fulfil the regular promises they have made, and give Maidenhead a minor injuries unit at St Mark&acirc;&#128;&#153;s Hospital.&rdquo;</em></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">St Marks Hospital, Health</p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/74''>74</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Hospital consultation covers fewer than one in&nbsp;five</h1>


<p class="published">14 April 2008</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Theresa May has today raised her concerns about how much local people in the Maidenhead area are being consulted by Berkshire East Primary Care Trust and Berkshire Healthcare Trust about plans to make significant changes to local healthcare services.</p>

	<p>Theresa says: <em>&ldquo;The Right Care, Right Place consultation has been running since January and proposes to make big changes to health services in Maidenhead. Despite repeated assurances that there could be a Minor Injuries Unit at St Marks Hospital, the current plans rule out this option. In addition the consultation raises the prospect of big changes to Charles ward at St Marks, which currently provides an invaluable service to elderly people with mental illnesses.&rdquo;</em></p>

	<p><em>&ldquo;Only 70,000 consultation booklets and questionnaires were send out to the public &ndash; this is a mere 18 per cent of the population serviced by Berkshire East <span class="caps">PCT</span>.&Acirc;&nbsp;The population of Maidenhead alone is 58,848! How can the Trust say it is giving people a real choice over healthcare and then ignore 82 per cent of us?&rdquo;</em></p>

	<p><em>&ldquo;Despite the consultation significantly improving health services in Bracknell and Slough, yet again, Maidenhead is being ignored.&Acirc;&nbsp;Thank goodness for the campaign run by the Maidenhead Advertiser &ndash; without that far fewer people would have been able to have their say on the plans.&rdquo;</em></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">St Marks Hospital, Health</p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/75''>75</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Theresa welcomes council rethink on Headington Close alley&nbsp;gate</h1>


<p class="published">24 April 2008</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Theresa May has welcomed the decision by the Royal Borough of Windsor and Maidenhead to install an alley gate in Headington Close in Maidenhead.</p>

	<p>Following complaints by local residents of Murrin Road and Headington Road, the Council had previously decided to install an alley gate in Murrin Road but ruled against doing the same in Headington Close, arguing that there were not enough reports of crime to justify it.</p>

	<p>However following a successful campaign by Theresa May and other concerned local residents, the Council have now reversed this decision and an alley gate is now in place in Headington Close.</p>

	<p>Commenting on this decision, Theresa said: <em>&ldquo;I am pleased that the Council have listened to what local residents are telling them and decided to install an alley gate at Headington Close after all.&rdquo;</em></p>

	<p><em>&ldquo;Two years ago a Headington Close resident, Mrs Rene Fairlie, died during a burglary at her house. The Royal Borough had been notified in advance by local residents about continuous disturbances and anti-social behaviour in the area, which made Mrs Fairlie&acirc;&#128;&#153;s death even more tragic.&rdquo;</em></p>

	<p><em>&ldquo;It has been proven that alley gates can help to lower the rate of crime and I hope that this gate will help local residents feel safer in their community.&rdquo;</em></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Law and Order, </p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/76''>76</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Theresa to run the &acirc;&#128;&#152;Race for Life&acirc;&#128;&#153;</h1>


<p class="published">29 April 2008</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>On 7th May Theresa May will be joining other female Conservative MPs to run the &lsquo;Race for Life&rsquo; in Battersea Park. As well as Theresa, &acirc;&#128;&#152;Team Tory&acirc;&#128;&#153; will include, among others, Conservative Party Chairman Caroline Spelman MP and Shadow Minister to the Treasury Justine Greening MP.</p>

	<p>Theresa and the team will be running/walking/jogging 5km in aid of Cancer Research UK and aim to raise &Acirc;&pound;1,000 to help Cancer Research fund its life-saving work into preventing, diagnosing and treating cancer. Anyone in Maidenhead who would like to sponsor the team and help raise money for Cancer Research can do so by visiting: <a href="http://www.raceforlifesponsorme.org/jenniegorbutt">http://www.raceforlifesponsorme.org/jenniegorbutt</a>.</p>

	<p>Your help and support is much appreciated.</p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Uncategorized, </p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/77''>77</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">MPs commend council&acirc;&#128;&#153;s motion on &acirc;&#128;&#152;garden grabbing&acirc;&#128;&#153;</h1>


<p class="published"> 1 May 2008</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Windsor and Maidenhead&acirc;&#128;&#153;s two Members of Parliament, Theresa May and Adam Afriyie, have today written to the leader of the Royal Borough of Windsor and Maidenhead, Councillor David Burbage, to commend the council&acirc;&#128;&#153;s motion regarding building on gardens.&Acirc;&nbsp;</p>

	<p>Planning rules which were brought in during John Prescott&acirc;&#128;&#153;s tenure as Deputy Prime Minister are forcing the demolition of homes with gardens, and their replacement with &acirc;&#128;&#152;high-density&acirc;&#128;&#153; developments.&Acirc;&nbsp;Local residents and their councils are increasingly powerless to prevent the over-development of their neighbourhoods, and infill of green spaces because of Government imposed top-down housing targets.</p>

	<p>The council motion, which was passed on 22nd April 2008, seeks to return powers over local planning decisions to locally elected councillors and follows a long-running campaign by Conservatives against Labour&acirc;&#128;&#153;s &acirc;&#128;&#156;garden grab&acirc;&#128;&#157;.&Acirc;&nbsp;</p>

	<p>Speaking about the motion, Theresa May said:</p>

	<p><em>&acirc;&#128;&#156;I am pleased that the Royal Borough is addressing the problem of garden grabbing. It is vital that we all work together to protect our local gardens which not only improve people&acirc;&#128;&#153;s personal quality of life, but also the feel of our local community. I know that many people in Maidenhead are concerned about this issue and I will continue to campaign with the Council and with Conservatives locally and nationally for an end to Labour&rsquo;s &lsquo;garden grab&rsquo;.&acirc;&#128;&#157;</em></p>

	<p>Adam Afriyie said:</p>

	<p><em>&acirc;&#128;&#156;I am delighted that the council are calling for powers over local planning decisions to be returned to local authorities.&Acirc;&nbsp;The insensitive over-development of our constituency is of great concern to me and I&acirc;&#128;&#153;ve been actively campaigning for the last few years and continue to do so now in Parliament.&Acirc;&nbsp;I would urge local residents to sign the Conservatives petition against Labour&acirc;&#128;&#153;s Garden Grab on the Conservatives website.&acirc;&#128;&#157;</em></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Housing and development, </p>
</div>
