<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/226''>226</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Theresa welcomes action to tackle local&nbsp;congestion</h1>


<p class="published"> 8 October 2012</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Theresa May has welcomed new investment in local infrastructure from the Government, which will see action taken to tackle congestion on local roads. The Government has today announced approval for a &Acirc;&pound;4.2 million scheme to alleviate congestion on the A404 by converting the Bisham roundabout to signalised crossroads. The scheme will be completed by 2015 and will help to reduce the high levels of congestion occurring daily on all four arms of the roundabout.</p>

	<p>The Secretary of State for Transport, Patrick McLoughlin, announced the scheme as part of plans to deliver 57 vital road improvements to boost the national economy, reduce congestion and improve safety. The &Acirc;&pound;170 million investment is part of a programme to keep traffic moving on England&acirc;&#128;&#153;s motorways and major A roads. The economic benefit of these 57 schemes is estimated at around &Acirc;&pound;3 billion.</p>

	<p>Commenting, Theresa said: &acirc;&#128;&#156;This is very welcome news and will help to tackle congestion on the A404 at Bisham, which is a constant source of frustration to local residents. The Government is right to invest in infrastructure and to support our vital transport links.&acirc;&#128;&#157;</p>

	<p>Patrick McLoughlin said: &acirc;&#128;&#156;Keeping traffic moving is vital to securing prosperity. By removing bottlenecks and improving access to local enterprise zones, key international trading ports and communities, these road schemes will help get people to and from work and power the economy. They also have the potential to help deliver more than 300,000 new jobs and 150,000 new homes.&rdquo;</p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Uncategorized, </p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/227''>227</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Boost for Maidenhead town&nbsp;centre</h1>


<p class="published">23 October 2012</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Theresa May has welcomed the news that the &acirc;&#128;&#152;Enjoy Maidenhead&acirc;&#128;&#153; Town Team has been named by the Government as one of its Town Team Partners, entitling it to increased support and finance. Town Team Partners will receive backing from a multi-million pound support programme to help put key elements of their plans into action as well as an advice and mentoring package.</p>

	<p>In August, the Government asked Members of Parliament to nominate their local Town Teams for the programme and the successful applicants have now been announced. Theresa nominated the &acirc;&#128;&#152;Enjoy Maidenhead&acirc;&#128;&#153; Town Team, which brings together the local authority, local Chamber of Commerce and local businesses and is working to improve Maidenhead town centre by making use of empty shops and bringing more activity to the High Street. As a Town Team Partner they will now receive &Acirc;&pound;10,000 towards this work and will have access to a network of advisers managed by the Association of Town Centre Management with direct mentoring and visits from a range of retail experts.</p>

	<p>Commenting, Theresa said: &acirc;&#128;&#156;I am very pleased that Maidenhead town centre will benefit from this increased support. Maidenhead has huge potential and, along with our wider work to rejuvenate the town centre, we can be optimistic about the town&acirc;&#128;&#153;s future. It is also a demonstration of the Government&acirc;&#128;&#153;s strong support for the future of town centres across the country.&acirc;&#128;&#157;</p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Maidenhead Town Centre, </p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/228''>228</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Theresa backs plans for new Free School in&nbsp;Holyport</h1>


<p class="published">26 October 2012</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Theresa May has backed proposals to establish a new Free School in Holyport. The proposals would see Holyport Free School established as a new day and boarding school in the state sector, on the site of the former Holyport Manor Special Educational Needs School. As a Free School, it would be non-selective and independent of the local authority. The school plans to open in September 2014 with a commitment to providing opportunities for pupils of all abilities and backgrounds to succeed.</p>

	<p>A public consultation has now opened, allowing local residents to express their views. Local parents are also able to register an interest in having their child attend the school. The consultation closes on 16th November 2012. Theresa has responded to the consultation and expressed her support for the school opening.</p>

	<p>Commenting, Theresa said: &acirc;&#128;&#156;Holyport Free School would be a welcome addition to educational provision in the Maidenhead area. The group behind this proposal have strong experience in education and have put together an impressive plan. I particularly support their commitment to providing the highest academic standards.&acirc;&#128;&#157; </p>

	<p>&acirc;&#128;&#156;It is important for people to know that &acirc;&#128;&#147; like all Free Schools &acirc;&#128;&#147; this school would be non-selective and open to children from all backgrounds. Holyport Free School has the potential to make a significant contribution to the quality of local education, and therefore to further improve the life-chances of children and young people in the local area.&acirc;&#128;&#157;</p>

	<p>For more information about the school <a href="http://www.holyportfreeschool.com">click here</a></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Education, </p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/229''>229</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Theresa urges progress on Kings Triangle&nbsp;project</h1>


<p class="published"> 7 December 2012</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Theresa May has urged the Royal Borough of Windsor &amp; Maidenhead to approve plans to redevelop the Kings Triangle area of Maidenhead town centre, ahead of a crucial planning meeting on 12th December. The meeting will decide whether to grant approval to an outline application submitted by developers, which will transform the area between King Street and Queen Street with new shops, homes and offices.</p>

	<p>The planning application was first submitted in November 2011 and has been subject to public consultation. Theresa has previously supported the proposals, stating that they should not be seen in isolation but are an important part of the wider efforts to rejuvenate Maidenhead town centre. She has now written to the Royal Borough&acirc;&#128;&#153;s Development Control Panel to support the application going ahead.</p>

	<p>Commenting, Theresa said: &acirc;&#128;&#156;The Kings Triangle site is a crucial one for Maidenhead town centre. These plans are a key element of the wider rejuvenation of the town centre that we all want to see. There are undoubtedly details of the plan that will need to be considered further in the future, but the outline application that has been submitted is an important step and is to be welcomed. If the application is turned down then there is a concern that it will further delay much-needed investment in Maidenhead and set back our efforts to regenerate the town centre.&acirc;&#128;&#157;</p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Maidenhead Town Centre, </p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/230''>230</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Theresa reacts to council decision to defer Kings Triangle&nbsp;decision</h1>


<p class="published">13 December 2012</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Theresa May has reacted to the Royal Borough of Windsor &amp; Maidenhead&acirc;&#128;&#153;s decision to defer planning permission for the Kings Triangle project in Maidenhead town centre. The decision was taken by the Royal Borough&acirc;&#128;&#153;s Development Control Panel and means that the project &acirc;&#128;&#147; which would bring new shops, homes and offices to the town centre &acirc;&#128;&#147; will be reconsidered in early 2013.</p>

	<p>Commenting, Theresa said: &acirc;&#128;&#156;The Kings Triangle site is a crucial one for Maidenhead town centre and I am concerned that a long delay will threaten much-needed investment in the town centre. The developers must now look at the concerns that led to the application not being approved at this time, and I hope that they can work with the Royal Borough to find solutions so that things can move forward in the New Year.&acirc;&#128;&#157;</p>

	<p>For more information on issues affecting Maidenhead town centre <a href="http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/?c=maidenhead-town-centre">click here</a></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Maidenhead Town Centre, </p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/231''>231</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Public meeting to discuss new hospital for Maidenhead&nbsp;area</h1>


<p class="published"> 8 January 2013</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Theresa May will be attending a public meeting this week to discuss proposals for a new hospital serving the Maidenhead area. The proposal to build a new hospital at Junction 8/9 of the M4, near Maidenhead, was first put forward by Theresa several years ago and has recently been taken forward by Dr Philip Lee, the MP for Bracknell, who has published a detailed report on how the new hospital could come into being. The public meeting will take place at the Maidenhead Holiday Inn on Thursday 10th January at 7:30pm.</p>

	<p>The meeting will be attended by Theresa and Dr Lee and is open to local residents who wish to hear more about the proposal or discuss issues relating to health services in Berkshire.</p>

	<p>Commenting, Theresa said: &acirc;&#128;&#156;I have long supported the concept of a new hospital at Junction 8/9 of the M4 and it is great that Philip Lee has been able to take this forward and publish new proposals. This is an important part of the wider debate about the <span class="caps">NHS</span> in Berkshire, and I will always look for opportunities to safeguard and enhance local services.&acirc;&#128;&#157;</p>

	<p>Philip Lee&acirc;&#128;&#153;s report is available <a href="http://www.phillip-lee.com/wp-content/uploads/the-royal-thames-valley-hospital.pdf">here</a></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">St Marks Hospital, </p>
</div>
