<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/307''>307</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Theresa urges electrification of the Thames Valley branch&nbsp;lines</h1>


<p class="published">27 May 2015</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Theresa May has expressed concern following indications that electrification of the Maidenhead to Marlow train line will not be going ahead in the near future. The Government&acirc;&#128;&#153;s electrification project will bring faster and more reliable trains along the Great Western line and it had been expected that the Thames Valley branch lines would also benefit. However, a recent report stated that it would not be &acirc;&#128;&#152;technically feasible&acirc;&#128;&#153; for electrification to go ahead on the Marlow branch, raising questions about the future of the Henley branch as well.</p>

	<p>The Department for Transport and Network Rail have consistently said that electrification of the branch lines would go ahead, allowing commuters in areas such as Furze Platt, Cookham and Wargrave to enjoy the benefits of the new electric trains. However, the Department for Transport&acirc;&#128;&#153;s recent response to a consultation on the next Great Western franchise stated that electrification on the Marlow branch could not go ahead before the end of the franchise in March 2019.</p>

	<p>Theresa has written to the Secretary of State for Transport, Patrick McLoughlin, to express concern and to ask for a clear timetable for electrification to go ahead on both the Marlow and Henley branches.</p>

	<p>Commenting, Theresa said: &acirc;&#128;&#156;Electrification will bring benefits to passengers and it is important that commuters on the branch lines don&acirc;&#128;&#153;t miss out. I have consistently supported the electrification of the branch lines and the continuation of through-services from the branches to London Paddington. I am now pressing for a clear timetable for the electrification of both branch lines so local residents have certainty about the services they can expect in the future.&acirc;&#128;&#157;</p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Trains, </p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/308''>308</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Support the Berkshire Disability&nbsp;Appeal</h1>


<p class="published"> 1 June 2015</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Theresa May is encouraging local residents to support the Berkshire Disability Appeal, which is raising money to support local people of all ages with physical, mental or learning disabilities. Money raised through the appeal will stay in the local community and go to where it is needed most &acirc;&#128;&#147; funding local charities and community groups doing vital grassroots work, helping to support people living with a disability.</p>

	<p>There are almost 110,000 people living in Berkshire with a long-term health problem or disability that limits their day-to-day activities &ndash; that is about 1 in 8 people.</p>

	<p>Berkshire Community Foundation already funds a wide range of disability charities and community groups across the whole of Berkshire. Through this dedicated appeal it hopes to be able to support many more organisations and improve the lives of thousands more people living with disabilities in Berkshire. </p>

	<p>People can donate to the appeal online at <a href="https://localgiving.com/charity/berkshiredisabilityappeal">www.localgiving.com/BerkshireDisabilityAppeal</a></p>

	<p>Donations by cheque can be sent to Berkshire Community Foundation, 100 Longwater Avenue, Green Park, Reading, RG2 6GP. Cheques should be made payable to &ldquo;Berkshire Community Foundation&rdquo; and clearly marked that the donation is for the Berkshire Disability Appeal.</p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Health, </p>
</div>
<hr/>
<a href='http://www.tmay.co.uk/news/309''>309</a><br/>
<div class="article-content">

<h1 class="article">Interview with the Maidenhead&nbsp;Advertiser</h1>


<p class="published">11 June 2015</p>


<div class="article-body">
	<p>Theresa May has spoken to the Maidenhead Advertiser about her plans for the next 5 years as the MP for Maidenhead. She highlighted her priorities for the constituency, including improving Maidenhead town centre and supporting vital train links with London. She also spoke about her role as Home Secretary, covering issues such as policing and immigration. To watch the interview, please visit the <a href="http://www.maidenhead-advertiser.co.uk/News/Areas/Maidenhead/VIDEO-Theresa-May-on-the-election-the-new-Government-term-and-Maidenheads-future-08062015.htm">Maidenhead Advertiser website</a></p>
</div>
<p class="article-category" style="display:none;">Maidenhead Town Centre, Trains</p>
</div>
